The high elven Goddess called the Loomkeeper of time; The dwarf God called the destiny Smith; The lizardfolk idol, the weirding spider; and even the Judge-scribe diety marked upon ancient lost monuments.

But the most credible sources all conclude that all spiders are her brood.

Many legends both good and evil have fought to pass through the doors into the house of the fatespinner but only those destined to enter, will.

It is believed that many gods and Goddesses are interpretations of her. Some such being. . .

As I fell back to you I no longer felt the webs in my hands. And I had no hope to contain the whole of what I had seen. But I know what I must. Those places where the threads meet. The faces I will cherish. The enemies I must face. And I know that I will be there to see the end."

Then the bright-widow took my hand and rested it upon the strands. We raced the paths and tied them into new configurations. and at last the work was over. I had crafted my destiny. And fell through eternity back to this place. And now that I am here it is all but forgotten.

I saw my Innumerable romances, and countless burning hatreds. I saw all that I could be. Death, war, peace, simplicity, immensity, immortality, annihilation, I saw in me the gods I may become and the fates that end abrupt and cold.

Few have gone beyond these hidden doors and fewer speak of it. But there is one account that reads.

"I saw my life all at once, every step that led me to that moment, and as my mind passed from past to future the endless web overtook me. Numbers beyond number of strands.

Her realm is a plane of existence hidden even to those who drift in the sea between creations. A place hidden but never lost. All things are connected. And her gates are found only by those destined to pass through them, Those invited to lay hold on the web of their own destiny.

There are those that skitter in the dark edges of eternity and pluck at the strings of fate. These she hunts and devours without remorse. but some are near in power to her and wars are waged on the fabric of destiny itself.

A patron goddess among the dark elves, she is said to be possessed of hope and to smaller extent love. She weaves fates for a final good end at the close of all things. But until then she coldly cuts those threads that do not contribute to what some call the Radiant Web.

Like all the gods she is seen differently from culture to culture. But one thing is certain. All spiders are descended directly from her. And some powerful ancient spiders help her weave the Fabric of Destiny. Despite her grotesque children she is no villain in our tale.

Lore of Tyr'Naiil

Destiny's Web

There is a primordial God. A formless being filled with purpose and power. She is the fateweaver, the mother of spiders, the Bright Widow. She spins the webs of fate and causality and decrees their final forms in her realm of infinite outcomes. https://t.co/tywYbfM0Pb

Availability Bias:

To judge the probabilities or verity of a concept by the ease of imagined examples, taken without regard for actual values.

"I can't imagine this working out so it must be impossible."

"I can think of 10 way this could work so it's a better option"

Now for me the easiest way to remember 10 is the 10th card of the tarot greater arcana, the wheel of fortune. I envision a man strapped to a wheel in a rakdos circus and people are throwing pies at him
10=pie
You now think 10. The straight item and the hole item together what was also involved with those? The image will return. Ah yes it was pie.

Let's say that the 10th item in a list is a pie. Imagine an exaggerated scenario involving the things you envisioned earlier and the pie in the same visual idea. Commit that image to memory.
When someone says "what's the 10th item on the list."

An example of pegging things in your memory.

For each sequenced number make an association. For example for the number 10 visualize something straight and something with a hole. Whenever something Is in the 10th place it must always be these two things.

Today I learned the numeric pegging system of memory.

It's called numeric pegging because you are pegging numbers full of meaning. Then making a visual of that pegging with the item that needs to be remembered in that pegged position.

One day you dream of a woman. Bloodied knuckles clutch at 4 lbs of sharpened steel, and in her arm a child. And you realize that this is no dream.

That child was you.

It was hard for you to engage with the strange minds of those around you. Having dreamed of so many people, seen their struggles how could your contemporaries judge each other by gender. Did they not dream of warrior women? Or by skills. Surely they have seen the swordless mage.

#dnd Writing prompt.

Every night for your entire life you had these dreams. Other spoke of dreams so you thought that everyone had vivid dreams of thousands of faces. Legendary deeds, happy lives, and squalorous uprisings.

You grew up wiser and erily discerning.

@akkator006 @4Kingdoms_TTRPG @OregonRolledA20 Bargain tmwith the Patron for greatly enhanced intelligence as part of the pact. Lore wise this is 100% kosher but it usually comes with a price. Just make sure the price no matter how steep is something you can back up.

@akkator006 @4Kingdoms_TTRPG @OregonRolledA20 Here's the kicker. And is something that can be a fun way to out lever the DM respectfully. @akkator006 @4Kingdoms_TTRPG @OregonRolledA20 There may be levels where he can't cast any of his newer spells because his int is too low. And he will grind until he's smart enough to figure it out.

@akkator006 @4Kingdoms_TTRPG @OregonRolledA20 If you want to multiclass warlock you can but only as many at 3 levels and you can make do with only one. Because you'll be wanting the invocations. Repulsing blast to maintain distance, devil's sight for REAL dark vision, and something like mask of many faces.

@akkator006 @4Kingdoms_TTRPG @OregonRolledA20 The reason the extra attacks are important is because with low stats you need every chance to get a hit rather than hoping to win big damage on a single shot

@akkator006 @4Kingdoms_TTRPG @OregonRolledA20 Because they are so low a lot of his spells will miss or fail so his that's why he relies on the teachings of his old mentor. Eldritch blast uses extra attacks as it levels and with aganizing blast the moment you buff cha it'll do more damage. Cruel feat will be very useful.

@akkator006 @4Kingdoms_TTRPG @OregonRolledA20 Any time he meets someone with a skill he think he can emulate he asks questions. He writes down what he sees and spends his spare time doing anything that qualifies as extra training to beef up his stats.
@akkator006 @4Kingdoms_TTRPG @OregonRolledA20 He wants to get those artifacts. Any of them that buff stats esp the circlet of intelect. But he'll take ogre power any day of the week if he can get it.

@akkator006 @4Kingdoms_TTRPG @OregonRolledA20 Because his academics were only introductory and he made it through almost by cheating he is only level 1 and he's around age 16-20. @akkator006 @4Kingdoms_TTRPG @OregonRolledA20 His warlock friend made asaw that because of his limited resources he wouldn't make it alone so he taught him how to fight with forbidden magics like hexes and eldritch blast (be sure to flavor the hell out of that blast, give it character)

@akkator006 @4Kingdoms_TTRPG @OregonRolledA20 In the competative world of arcane academia amidst nobles there is infighting and even subterfuge and murder. @akkator006 @4Kingdoms_TTRPG @OregonRolledA20 Cruel feat so at any time you can spend a point to deal 1d6 extra damage on your goblins or what have you.

@akkator006 @4Kingdoms_TTRPG @OregonRolledA20 Once you get past those rough early levels. Spell sniper to get in those hard to reach places but only if your DM is clever. If he doesn't use terrain based combat then don't bother.

But what would a culture that represents the unification of these three states look like?

A religious, Reformed, collective?
A hive of Enlightened Zealots.

Very powerful. Very powerful indeed.

So it is my guestimation that there are three powerful templates on the galactic scale

The Zealot (covenant, imperium of man)
The Hive (the zerg, the Protos, the Borg)
The Reformed (the federation, the Tau, the Jedi)

While it's effects are utopian it's structure is unsound without some external factor, such as the very dangerous philosophical field of eugenics or radical degrees of cultural therapy, (philanthropic or otherwise)

Greed, expansionism, violence, and mistrust are requirements for survival up until this stage. Anything less is too weak to survive any carnivorous world. To turn that around has harsh effects on the biology of such creatures.

This is simultaneously the weakest and strongest of the three. Such a culture cannot have it's hivemind compromised, nor does it stagnate under archtypical thinking. It is however counterintuitive to advancement and also is against the biology of most creatures.

This is the area of star treks federation. Where an entire culture has no need of currency because each has food to eat and works for the greater good. Internal conflict rendered obsolete. A culture of self control.

The last and least likely is enlightenment. A civilization needing neither illusions nor mind powers to enforce unity. Where an entire culture Can on their own through philosophical understanding work as one for a common goal.
Terrifying but effective. A religious civilization can easily claim the stars as their own so long their code allows it. Their greatest weakness being stagnation of thought and disillusionment.

Where the hive is sensitive to the guilt of any and this may catalyze the evolution of philosophy, The Order moves forward by machination only to be steered. All understand the law, they know their enemy. To dissent against this is crime of the unholiest calibur.

The threat of heresy, the looming danger of the demon, these varied zeitgeists keep each suspended in vigilance and ready to act upon the preconceived. This state is easily directed by the holiest among them.

The code, the devil, the angel, heaven, hell, repentance, absolution. With a simple set of unifying characteristics drawing the minds of billions together you maintain unity while permitting conflict.

Religion has its own results. Probably the most popular in modern sci-fi for advanced civs. In this scenario the unity of belief drives the order forward towards each goal. Easy to controll in general with the emergence of the archtype.

But a truely effective hivemind would be a collective of individual minds. Where within the ancestral memory of the collective the thread can be seen.

The needs of the many are the needs of the one. When the needs of the many are resolved so too are those of the one.

As much as I appreciate individualism I must say that it does breed its own special brand of inane stupidity and in the end feeds into a new manner of hivemind where no information is actually transfered.

My favored variant is hive mind. Though feared for a perceived lack of individual identity one cannot deny it's effectiveness, When all members of the collective can act without delay on the consensus of the whole, and 10,000 minds can seek out a solution to a single question.

#scifi

The advancement required for an advance spacefaring civilization is unity.

So long as division remains a factor the threat of anihilation, stagnation, and retreat are inevitable. I suspect the majority of advanced civs are hivemind, religious, or enlightened.

Naturally all rolls must be left on the table to permit accusation but each player has a small cover or screen or cup such as in liars dice.
Each trespass, accusation, and severity is written down. As each use of the chart has in-game significance as it represents interference of the Gods in the affairs of mortals.

Naturally this would require a playgroup that is comfortable with each other, and that all players understand the kind of game they are getting into. But if you have a playgroup that's fun, cheeky, smart, and underhanded you might make the game more fun.

There is a chart of boons and banes with die rolls. If at any time an accusation is made and can be proved false then then it qualifies as catching the other individual cheating and the accused may choose from the table instead of rolling.

If the player catches the DM cheating, the player gains a boon. Advantage on all rolls for the next three turns, inspiration, an extra max level spell slot for the encounter, or maybe even a single free wish that the DM may still try to cheat you out of as per wish rulings.

If the DM catches a player cheating then he chooses some manner of bane to place on that player equal to the cheat. Fudging a skill check might offer the sickened condition, adding damage dice might cause something to backfire.

And all these are not just adventurers. But heroes of light who brought hope to wherever they went.

If you truely wish to attend this fools errand I recommend you go to the meadow first, you'll need it for the battles ahead.

Many who go to this meadow whether they be great adventurers already or new travelers often find that their legend has only just begun.

Taryk Barnholf once went there.
Seville Montgaes, Fiona Retremon, Ruprecht Du'pont, and Klein Fleischer all went there in their travels.

Not crushingly alone at all. Just knowing that the child was never there and neither was the shut-in. But inside you still feel their hearts. The shut-in loves you. The child loves you and watches you, growing inside your heart.

You watch yourself slowly fall in love with someone from many angles. Until finally you three leave the meadow. Child abuzz with the days novelty, the shut-in getting some needed light, and the traveler at peace.

Then you realize that you are alone.

But in the end it is always the same. Twilight comes and there is a dance, or a kiss, maybe more. And the two make way to the cottage and the child greets them and is so happy. And you consciousness flits between child, traveler, and shut-in.

You go out to meet the stranger ready to drive off the person who came to upset your home, but are struck by the sight of that stranger. Definitely, strange but quite appealing this traveler is. You wake up this traveler and what manner of conversation ensues depends.

Usually food is made and this person in the cottage listens to the child ramble, about their adventure with the stranger.  This person will care first for the child then somewhere between eating and tucking the child in you are no more the child but the shut-in

The tales differ a lot from this point. But in the house there is always a person who is very different from the person who entered the field. I presume an antithesis to all the traveler perceives themself to be.

And somewhere between laying yourself down and closing your eyes you realize that you are not the visitor but the child, taking care of this strange adult. The traveler rests now and the child runs off to a house in the woods. And cries "Mommy!" Or "daddy! There's a stranger!"

You see a little child usually not the same gender as yourself, it will run up to you and ask you silly questions, questions only a child wouod come up with. You will start to become foggy and tired and the child will tuck you in to sleep on the ground.

But if they allow you in, you may find the peace you seek. The feyfolk there have long ago made a pact, I know not who with, to heal those who travel through.

When you reach that place there's no telling what you will see but there is one tale that is most common there.

Fogs of Magic and color, darting lights, and quiet voices always too quiet to make out. Yes, it is a fae realm. But, there you need not fear, for they bring little harm even to the darkest visitor. Those not welcome will always come out of the woods tired but well.

#dnd #storytime

That was the last time she would ever see her home. The mages greeted her at her coming. Her village had been destroyed and it's people slain or taken, by an unknown group. But that was not the last note her child would write. For that night was on parchment

"C H rOn O MA N Cy"

"what about. . ."

"I will go to the village and if all is well for a fortnight I shall send your husband to retrieve you and my token. The mages can talk with me and I with them so whatever happens we will know the matter soon. Take my horse and go."

"where will I go?"

"Take the forest road to Filshire and look for my chapter house. Give the door man this token and wait there. Do exactly as my fellows order. They will lodge you but not for free. They will likely have you washing plates for them while you stay."

"is your husband a violent man against you?"

"Certainly not. He is very kind."

"it is plain to me that you child has written this note and desires your safety. And if it is not for your father's sake this is ominous indeed. Sling your child and take my horse."

Pressing his thumb softly to the boys forehead his eyes glaze over and glow a pale blue as he mutters. Before returning to brown.

"Impossible!"

"What is it?"

"I sought out the child's true name but it is hidden from me."

"By what?"

"By the child. He resisted my magics."

"it means there are no demons, fae, or other evils at work with this note but. . . Hand me your child."

"What?"

"I would handle your child, did you not come here for my help?!"

She reluctantly passes the child to his arms. He begins a new incantation.

He looked in her arms and saw the child exhaustedly asleep 
"They read 'Run away mom' pardon me I will cast a spell." He spoke a brief incantation as runes filled the air.

The parchment glowed a faint silver light.

"What does that mean?"

"can you read girl?"

"No. But I have seen letters. These are letters yes?"

"Without a doubt these are letters written by an unskilled penman. These are your work?"

"I found them beside a charcoal in my son's crib. Noone else is in our house. What do the letters say?"

And soon she was at the home of an old mage working among his tomes.

"Damned simple-folk! What is it woman!? I was in the middle of something!"

"Explain to me these letters!"

"What?! You make demands of. . ." 
He saw her terror and pulled up his glasses with a huff

There was only one she know that could make sense of such ominous things. She would go to the wizard. His House is a short way in the woods.

Many saw her fearfully distress and tried to calm her but she brushed them aside with apologies and kurt "good mornings"

As she looked down she saw the child had clutched the parchment and continued wailing as he struck her with it as his hands grew weak the parchment fell.

She snatched the page, covered her child and moved as quickly as she could without jostling her precious son.

"The Hells!?" She whispers as she reads the parchment. Noone was there to plant such a poor joke. Surely an infant cannot write. She picked up the child and made warding gestures against evil with her spare hand. Could there be fae in the house playing their tricks?

This cannot be. How did he acquire the materials to do this? How could he have conceived of things he hasn't been taught? Yet within the crib was a crumbled piece of paper, A piece of charcoal, and on the paper we're jagged scrawled letters

r U N A w AY Mo M
